Angioedema with conjunctival injection, rhinorrhea, syncope, and pruritus is most suggestive of an acute allergic reaction. Common causes of acute allergic reactions include food allergies, insect stings, and medication allergies.
Hereditary angioedema (HAE) is a rare genetic disorder that can cause angioedema. HAE attacks can be triggered by a variety of factors, including stress, trauma, and certain medications.
Mastocytosis is another rare disorder that can cause angioedema. Mastocytosis is caused by an abnormal accumulation of mast cells in the body.
These are just a few of the possible diagnoses for the combination of symptoms you provided. It is important to see a doctor for a diagnosis and treatment plan.
Flushing and vomiting may indicate carcinoid syndrome, a rare condition caused by a tumor that releases hormones and other substances.
Flushing, pruritis, and conjunctival injection may be symptoms of allergic conjunctivitis, an inflammation of the conjunctiva caused by an allergy.
Flushing and pruritis may be symptoms of a mastocytosis, a rare condition characterized by an overgrowth of mast cells in the body.
